06667nam a22009615i 9783110594560DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20182019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105945607 a10.1515/97831105945602doi  a(DE-B1597)494122  a(OCoLC)1083622315  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aBS718b.O347 2019 7aREL0064102bisacsh04a221.44223  aBC 6005qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/9495:1 aOfer, Yosef, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Masora on Scripture and Its Methods /cYosef Ofer. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (XII, 286 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aFontes et Subsidia ad Bibliam pertinentes ,x1861-602X ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tPart I: The Biblical Masora and its Methods -- t1. What is the Masora? -- t2. Methods of Description and Classification -- t3. Determining Orthography on the Basis of Masoretic Notes -- t4. The Accumulative Masora -- t5. Open and Closed Passages and the Writing of Songs -- t6. Ketiv and Qere -- t7. The Masora on Scripture as an “Error Correcting Code” -- tPart II: The Masoretic Text in Time and Space -- t8. The Aleppo Codex and its Discovery -- t9. The Babylonian Masora and Its Influence -- t10. The Masoretic Text and its Role in the History of the Text of Scripture -- t11. Secondary Stress Marks (Ge’ayot) – in Manuscripts and in Printed Editions -- t12. Published Editions of the Hebrew Bible – and Their Relation to the Masora and the Aleppo Codex -- tPart III: The Masora in Interaction with Other Disciplines -- t13. The Masora and Hebrew Grammar -- t14. The Masora and Biblical Exegesis -- t15. The Masora and Halakha -- tIndex of Manuscripts -- tIndex of People -- tIndex of Terms0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe starting point for any study of the Bible is the text of the Masora, as designed by the Masoretes. The ancient manuscripts of the Hebrew Bible contain thousands of Masora comments of two types: Masora Magna and Masora Prava. How does this complex defense mechanism, which contains counting of words and combinations from the Bible, work?Yosef Ofer, of Bar-Ilan University and the Academy of the Hebrew Language, presents the way in which the Masoretic comments preserve the Masoretic Text of the Bible throughout generations and all over the world, providing comprehensive information in a short and efficient manner.The book describes the important manuscripts of the Hebrew Bible, and the methods of the Masora in determining the biblical spelling and designing the forms of the parshiot and the biblical Songs. The effectiveness of Masoretic mechanisms and their degree of success in preserving the text is examined. A special explanation is offered for the phenomenon of qere and ketiv.The book discusses the place of the Masoretic text in the history of the Bible, the differences between the Babylonian Masora and that of Tiberias, the special status of the Aleppo Codex and the mystery surrounding it. Special attention is given to the comparison between the Aleppo Codex and the Leningrad Codex (B 19a). In addition, the book discusses the relationship between the Masora and other tangential domains: the grammar of the Hebrew language, the interpretation of the Bible, and the Halakha.The book is a necessary tool for anyone interested in the text of the Bible and its crystallization.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aMasorah. 4aBiblische Handschrift. 4aMasora. 4aMasoretischer Text. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Reference / Language Study.2bisacsh  aBiblical Manuscripts.  aKetiv and Qere.  aThe Masora.  aThe Masoretic Text.08iTitle is part o